ights to the ones raging in Germany, Italy, and Spain. As he traces the global trajectory of the antifascist movement, Fronczak argues that its most significant legacy is its creation of “the left” as we know it today: an international conglomeration of people committed to a shared politics of solidarity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aAnti-fascist movementsxHistoryy20th century. 0aFascismxHistoryy20th century. 0aFascismxPrevention. 0aLiberalismxHistoryy20th century. 0aRight and left (Political science)xHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074978640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300268591?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300268591423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300268591/original  a978-3-11-074978-6  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY